\begin{CRITIC}
*   **Data-Hypothesis Mismatch**: The proposed "scaling collapse" assumes a single self-similar attractor. However, the dataset includes mechanisms (e.g., PM maps, Sisyphus cooling) that are inherently non-stationary or possess finite-time correlations that deviate from the fractional Fokker-Planck (FFP) limit. You lack the temporal resolution (only 500-5000 steps) to distinguish between true asymptotic convergence and transient pre-asymptotic behavior.
*   **Feasibility Gap**: Estimating the characteristic function $\phi(k, t)$ from only 200 trajectories is statistically ill-posed. The high-frequency components of the Fourier transform will be dominated by sampling noise, rendering the "deviation from exponential decay" metric unreliable for identifying universality classes.
*   **Redundancy/Slop**: The "attraction strength" metric is ill-defined. Without a rigorous definition of the distance metric between the empirical PDF and the Lévy-stable PDF (e.g., Kullback-Leibler divergence or Wasserstein distance), this is qualitative hand-waving rather than a quantitative physical theory.
*   **Strategic Pivot**: Abandon the "universal attractor" search. Instead, perform a **Finite-Time Scaling Analysis**. Map the effective Hurst exponent $H(t)$ and the tail index $\alpha(t)$ as a function of time. Use the 200 trajectories to calculate the *rate of convergence* to the Lévy-stable limit. This identifies which mechanisms are "fast" vs. "slow" to reach the FFP regime, providing a more robust classification than a binary "is it a Lévy flight" test.
*   **Weak Link**: The assumption that all mechanisms converge to the same $\mathcal{L}_\alpha$ ignores the fundamental difference between *jump-based* (CTRW/Lorentz) and *velocity-based* (Sisyphus) mechanisms. The latter may never reach the FFP limit due to the coupling between momentum and position.
\end{CRITIC}


