\begin{CRITIC}
*   **Data-Hypothesis Mismatch**: The $W_1$ (Wasserstein) distance is highly sensitive to the support of the distribution. Because the "Pure Lévy" reference and the physical mechanisms (e.g., Sisyphus cooling) operate on different physical scales and boundary conditions, $W_1$ will be dominated by scale-mismatch noise rather than structural convergence.
*   **Feasibility Gap**: The Hurst exponent $H(t)$ is notoriously unstable for finite-time series (N=200 trajectories). Calculating a derivative $d \ln \langle x^2 \rangle / d \ln t$ on noisy, finite-length data will produce high-variance artifacts, rendering the "fast-convergent" vs. "transient-dominant" classification statistically insignificant.
*   **Physical Reality**: The Sisyphus cooling mechanism is a momentum-dependent friction model. Its position distribution is not necessarily a Lévy-stable process; it is a Tsallis-distributed process. Forcing a $W_1$ comparison against a pure Lévy-stable reference is a category error—you are measuring the distance to a model that may not be the correct attractor.
*   **Redundancy**: This is a refinement of Iteration 0, but it replaces a robust (though difficult) Fourier-space analysis with a metric ($W_1$) that is mathematically ill-suited for comparing processes with different underlying physical constraints.
*   **Strategic Pivot**: Abandon the $W_1$ convergence rate. Instead, perform a **Rescaled Range (R/S) Analysis** or **Detrended Fluctuation Analysis (DFA)** to extract the scaling exponent $H$ across multiple time-scales. Use the **Kullback-Leibler (KL) Divergence** on the *normalized* PDFs (scaled by $t^{1/\alpha}$) to compare the shape of the tails against the Lévy-stable reference, rather than the absolute distance. This isolates the "Lévy-ness" of the mechanism from the scale-dependent drift.
\end{CRITIC}


