Idea: **Title: Universal Scaling Attractors in Anomalous Diffusion: A Comparative Propagator Analysis**

This study establishes a unified effective theory by testing the convergence of disparate microscopic mechanisms—Pomeau-Manneville intermittency, CTRW, Lévy-Lorentz gas, and Sisyphus cooling—toward a common Lévy-stable attractor. For each mechanism, we will compute the empirical probability density function $P(x, t)$ and perform a scaling collapse onto the self-similar form $P(x, t) = t^{-1/\alpha} \mathcal{L}_\alpha(x/t^{1/\alpha})$, where $\mathcal{L}_\alpha$ is the Lévy-stable PDF. By systematically varying the control parameters (e.g., $z$ in PM maps, $\alpha$ in Lorentz gas, and $\gamma_0$ in Sisyphus cooling), we will quantify the "attraction strength" of each system toward the fractional Fokker-Planck limit. We will evaluate the fidelity of this convergence by measuring the deviation of the characteristic function $\phi(k, t)$ from the theoretical exponential decay $\exp(-D_\alpha |k|^\alpha t)$. This approach identifies which physical mechanisms possess the minimal parameter set required to replicate genuine Lévy-stable statistics, effectively mapping the universality classes of anomalous diffusion within the provided synthetic trajectory space.


